        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i
              >Nelson Mandela and Winnie Mandela raise black power salutes in
              Johannesburg, on February 13, 1990, shortly after his release from
              prison. Credits: Udo Weitz/AP</i
            >
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            Unlike colonial independence, South Africa’s key milestone came from
            the end of
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-5-jul-25-iatw-h4-7-apartheid"
              target="_blank"
              >apartheid</a
            >, a system of institutionalized racial segregation. In 1994, the
            country held its first democratic elections, electing Nelson Mandela
            as President. South Africa emerged as the dominant voice in Southern
            Africa, a founding member of BRICS, and a mediator in African
            conflicts.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>Did you know?</strong> Mandela voted for the first time at
            the age of 75, having spent
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-5-jul-25-iatw-h4-8-27-years-in-prison"
              target="_blank"
              >27 years in prison</a
            >
            before becoming President.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
